[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":341},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F25\u002Flearn-hexo-12-basic-git-commands\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F25\u002Flearn-hexo-12-basic-git-commands\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F25\u002Flearn-hexo-12-basic-git-commands\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F25\u002Flearn-hexo-12-basic-git-commands\u002F":318,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F25\u002Flearn-hexo-12-basic-git-commands\u002F":327},"\u002Fhexo\u002F20200925\u002F1602283117\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":299,"date":300,"description":19,"extension":301,"lang":302,"meta":303,"navigation":304,"path":305,"readingMinutes":306,"seo":307,"standalone":308,"stem":309,"tags":310,"tldr":315,"updated":300,"url":316,"__hash__":317},"content\u002Fen\u002FHexo\u002Flearn-hexo-12-basic-git-commands.md","(12) Learning Hexo from Scratch - Basic Git Commands You Can't Skip","7113822061",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":289},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,57,60,64,74,80,87,93,97,126,136,142,146,164,167,173,177,180,183,206,219,241,245,253,257,260,285],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"This post covers the most basic git commands. Otherwise, what's going to happen to your Hexo project?",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"basic-commands","Basic commands",[17,25,26],{},"Since we're using GitHub Pages as our blog host, you need at least these basic git commands — otherwise, where are you going to put your Hexo source code and posts?",[28,29,30,37,42,47,52],"ul",{},[31,32,33],"li",{},[34,35,36],"code",{},"git init",[31,38,39],{},[34,40,41],{},"git add",[31,43,44],{},[34,45,46],{},"git commit",[31,48,49],{},[34,50,51],{},"git push",[31,53,54],{},[34,55,56],{},"git clone",[17,58,59],{},"The walkthrough below assumes you've already installed git.",[12,61,63],{"id":62},"git-init-initialise-a-repo","git init (initialise a repo)",[17,65,66,67,69,70,73],{},"Initialises a git repo. You only really run this once — the very first time you set up a project for version control. The goal is to version-control your Hexo source. Try running ",[34,68,36],{}," in your Hexo folder. After it runs, you'll see a hidden ",[34,71,72],{},".git"," folder appear:",[17,75,76],{},[77,78],"img",{"alt":72,"src":79},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-09%2020.51.01.png",[17,81,82,83,86],{},"Your terminal will print something like ",[34,84,85],{},"Initialized empty Git repository in \u002FUsers\u002Frayxu\u002FitHelp\u002FitHelpHexo\u002F.git\u002F",", which means your project is now under git version control. If you're in VSCode, you'll also notice files have turned green and light grey (green = can be staged, grey = ignored).",[17,88,89],{},[77,90],{"alt":91,"src":92},"VSCode","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-09%2020.52.02.png",[12,94,96],{"id":95},"git-add-stage-files","git add (stage files)",[17,98,99,101,102,105,106,109,110,113,114,117,118,121,122,125],{},[34,100,41],{}," stages a specific file — e.g. ",[34,103,104],{},"git add index.html"," to stage ",[34,107,108],{},"index.html",". With Hexo, I mostly just run ",[34,111,112],{},"git add ."," or ",[34,115,116],{},"git add -A",", which stage everything. ",[34,119,120],{},"."," and ",[34,123,124],{},"-A"," mean the same thing here.",[17,127,128,129,131,132,135],{},"After ",[34,130,112],{}," on the Hexo source, you won't see anything happen — you need ",[34,133,134],{},"git status"," to check the current state. Staged files will look something like this:",[17,137,138],{},[77,139],{"alt":140,"src":141},"Staged","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-09%2021.11.12.png",[12,143,145],{"id":144},"git-commit-commit-your-changes","git commit (commit your changes)",[17,147,148,150,151,121,154,157,158,160,161,120],{},[34,149,46],{}," has two main flags worth knowing: ",[34,152,153],{},"-a",[34,155,156],{},"-m",". The more common one is ",[34,159,156],{},", which adds a commit message. For our first source upload, you'd run ",[34,162,163],{},"git commit -m 'first'",[17,165,166],{},"Once it runs you'll see something like this:",[17,168,169],{},[77,170],{"alt":171,"src":172},"commit","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FHexo\u002F%E8%A9%A6%E8%91%97%E5%AD%B8%20Hexo%20%E7%B3%BB%E5%88%97\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-08-09%2021.15.32.png",[12,174,176],{"id":175},"git-push-push-to-remote","git push (push to remote)",[17,178,179],{},"This last one requires a GitHub remote. Personally I use a Private repo for my Hexo source. I won't walk through creating the repo — it's the same concept as \"Creating a GitHub Pages repo\" from the previous post.",[17,181,182],{},"Once you've created the repo, you'll usually see commands like:",[184,185,190],"pre",{"className":186,"code":187,"language":188,"meta":189,"style":189},"language-cmd shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","git remote add origin https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fhsianghexo\u002Fhexo.git\ngit push -u origin master\n","cmd","",[34,191,192,200],{"__ignoreMap":189},[193,194,197],"span",{"class":195,"line":196},"line",1,[193,198,199],{},"git remote add origin https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fhsianghexo\u002Fhexo.git\n",[193,201,203],{"class":195,"line":202},2,[193,204,205],{},"git push -u origin master\n",[17,207,208,211,212,215,216,120],{},[34,209,210],{},"git remote add origin"," means: add a new remote called ",[34,213,214],{},"origin",", pointing at ",[34,217,218],{},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fhsianghexo\u002Fhexo.git",[17,220,221,224,225,228,229,231,232,235,236,238,239,120],{},[34,222,223],{},"git push -u origin master"," means: push to the ",[34,226,227],{},"master"," branch on ",[34,230,214],{},". What's ",[34,233,234],{},"-u","? That flag tells git to remember this push relationship, so next time you can just run ",[34,237,51],{}," instead of ",[34,240,223],{},[12,242,244],{"id":243},"git-clone-copy-a-repo","git clone (copy a repo)",[17,246,247,248,250,251,120],{},"You'll see this one most when switching machines or handing a project off to someone else. Two benefits: first, it auto-initialises the git project for you; second, it auto-sets the ",[34,249,223],{}," relationship, so subsequent pushes are just ",[34,252,51],{},[12,254,256],{"id":255},"extra-reading","Extra reading",[17,258,259],{},"git concepts go beyond the scope of this series, so if you want to dig in, here's what I'd recommend:",[28,261,262,271,278],{},[31,263,264],{},[265,266,270],"a",{"href":267,"rel":268},"https:\u002F\u002Fgitbook.tw\u002F",[269],"nofollow","Learn Git by Yourself (Mandarin)",[31,272,273],{},[265,274,277],{"href":275,"rel":276},"https:\u002F\u002Fw3c.hexschool.com\u002Fgit\u002Fcfdbd310",[269],"Git & GitHub Tutorial Manual (Mandarin)",[31,279,280],{},[265,281,284],{"href":282,"rel":283},"https:\u002F\u002Fbacklog.com\u002Fgit-tutorial\u002Ftw\u002Fintro\u002Fintro1_1.html",[269],"Even a Monkey Can Understand Git (Mandarin)",[286,287,288],"style",{},"html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}",{"title":189,"searchDepth":202,"depth":202,"links":290},[291,292,293,294,295,296,297,298],{"id":14,"depth":202,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":2